  number = {6},
  month = {Jun},
  abstract = {When a beneficial mutation is fixed in a population that lacks recombination,
	the genetic background linked to that mutation is fixed. As a result,
	beneficial mutations on different backgrounds experience competition,
	or "clonal interference," that can cause asexual populations to evolve
	more slowly than their sexual counterparts. Factors such as a large
	population size (N) and high mutation rates (mu) increase the number
	of competing beneficial mutations, and hence are expected to increase
	the intensity of clonal interference. However, recent theory suggests
	that, with very large values of Nmu, the severity of clonal interference
	may instead decline. The reason is that, with large Nmu, genomes
	including both beneficial mutations are rapidly created by recurrent
	mutation, obviating the need for recombination. Here, we analyze
	data from experimentally evolved asexual populations of a bacteriophage
	and find that, in these nonrecombining populations with very large
	Nmu, recurrent mutation does appear to ameliorate this cost of asexuality.},
